{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0b5e1bc4-07aa-41bb-b5bc-9ef5c0237250","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — if enabled:\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores typically land in /cores/\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Note: SIP (System Integrity Protection) may prevent core dump generation.\n\n3. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view of the same `.ips` files.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and register state — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2fa84d68-3a9f-4e1c-b757-465ff28e72fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":294,"requestId":"4193:11463F:62EC822:6C27C3B:69F16373"},"id":"ea82c2dd-082c-498c-951f-f375771a8d09","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:48:44.008Z","parentId":"2b1ea9ca-e1f7-4c42-920b-ef2ff7911da7"}
